I had a regular rubber bath mat I was using in the tub. Every day after showering, I would hang it up in an attempt to dry it out. But mold grew on it anyway, and it was impossible to clean. I started to feel as if keeping the mat clean was my second job!

I started researching other options, and I came to the conclusion that 3M knew that they're doing when it comes to adhesives. I originally had the one-inch strips in my cart, but I saw the two-inch option so I switched. I'm glad I did. You get double the coverage with the same amount of effort.

I have a old, standard-size tub, and one package covered nicely. A relative's tub is new and a bit larger; I had to order a second package to complete the job.

Before applying, I cleaned the tub as others have recommended. I used rubbing alcohol to remove any remaining residue. Then I used a hair dryer to make sure any moisture was gone. I cut the strips and rounded them off using a spice jar as a template. They cut easily with regular scissors.

Edited to add: A very important step is to BURNISH each strip after you apply it. You need to get the air bubbles out and ensure a good grip. If you happen to have a wallpaper roller, as others have said, I bet that would work. But if you don't, you can use any plastic bottle. I used a deodorant tube, or a shampoo bottle would be fine too. Just don't skip this step!

It's been about six weeks so far, and the strips are sticking beautifully. We really love not having to deal with a tub mat all the time.

Good value for the money, very easy to cut and easy to install. Thick for my needs, used as-is it restricted air flow, but was able to easily split the material and I am now actually getting double for the money from that pov. The velcro tape is not enough if you have several large vents you need to cover. I am using this on the supply side of my window/wall ac units and the vents are about 19x4 inches and I need velcro tape all around to hold in place. I expect these to dramatically reduce dust (and mold) that's blown in by my cemented into the wall, window air conditioners. Will do an update in a little while when I change the filters.

UPDATE - its been a while now since my first review and had a chance to test out the efficacy of this product.

The morning after placing the filter over the output end of my ac as you can see in the video, part of it had come unglued... not the filter off of the tape, but the tape off of the AC. It wouldn't stick and stay back on after that. I had done the same thing to a different AC and over there everything stayed in place to this day. I guess you should make sure the tape is fully glued to a solid surface and maybe let it sit for a minute before turning the AC on - if you are going to use it in the same manner I did.

I did notice however that even tho air was flowing thru the filter (which I had split in half) the room was staying at a higher temperature than the setting on the AC or than it was before installing the filter... and it felt like the AC unit was working harder too, sadly, I had to undo the filter in parts and actually ended removing it altogether on the other unit.

I really wanted this to work and I'm still thinking of ways of making it work.. perhaps if I try an even thinner layer.. or maybe use it during the cooler months (I live in Miami)..

I find that the adhesive side on some of the velcro stripes were not sticky enough, then I had to use little drops of glue.  Also, some complained that it restricted airflow.  The easy fix is to stretch the middle part of the filter (where the vent area surface would be.  obviously, not to a point where it has holes but just thinner).  I also sprayed a little fabreeze on the filter.  every time the AC comes on, smell the scent.  lol.  we will see how long the filter sticks to the velcro.

Great for tubs, showers, and really anything else that needs more grip.  Used the one inch tape in my shower and in my girlfriends death tub they felt like it was oiled down at all times.  Used more than a roll for the tub the way I did it, less than a roll for the shower, but the both the shower and tub were just short of two rolls.  Larger gaps or use two inch tape and I'm sure one roll will suffice in a bath tub.  Also bought the two inch tape just to be able to add this tape to other items.  Bought a 40 oz water bottle that had decent weight when full and had a slick finish.  Adding some of this tape to the outside drastically improved the bottle.  Also added to many other items including gun grips, zippo, knives, and even nail clippers(highly recommended, makes life easier).  Also have 3M grip tape for outdoor stairs thats black and way more aggressive that works great as well but it's pretty much super course sandpaper so gotta be careful what you put that on because it can really mess up something that rubs against it so thats where this clear tape comes in handy.  Adds grip to slick surfaces but not abrasive to the point where its damaging.

Then summer heat in Texas hit and we realized that the room we put it on the vent in (our bedroom) was SIGNIFICATNLY hotter than the entire house (like it was 81 in our room when the rest of the house was 73). We tried everythingâinsulators on the window, oscillating fans, leaving the door open, closing other vents, checking the wall insulation, literally everything.

Then my husband tried taking OFF this filter at 2pm on a 104 degree day and within 30 MINUTES it was 5 degrees cooler.

I'm sad.

I wish this worked without hindering air flow, but despite the other reviews I read, it in fact DOES reduce air flow :(

I recently moved into an apartment complex that was supposed to be pest free and smoke free Couple of days after moving in we started smelling a lot of cigarettes smoke and weed as well. We first thought it was coming from the door or windows, since people would go to the balconies to smoke, but nope we learned that our next door neighbor smokes inside and the smoke smell comes from all the ac vents and the bathroom vent when the AC is not running. I got this ace filter to cover the AC vents. I sprayed the filter with odor ban to see if it helps. I will let you guys know more about its efficiency after couple of days.

I decided to cover the vents from the inside, so I could still redirect the vent from the outside, and because of that I used a lot of the fabric. I live in a 1 bedroom apartment, so I only have 3 ac vents to cover. I covered all of them and have enough fabric to change all of them once more with a little bit to spare, but if you cover from the front I would say you should have enough for a good 28 vents.

I am writing a review, as I am a HUGE review reader. How do you know what you are getting if you don't get feedback from people who have bought it, right?! I was a little skeptical at first, as some stated it blocked airflow and created their system to work harder. In reading the reviews, there was a verified buyer that stated she was able to pull the material apart so that the material wasn't so thick. I did this very same thing with ease when I received my filter. It was almost as if you could see exactly where you needed to pull it apart to get half the filter.

The other complaint was that the tape was not sticky enough. OK, I am an anal freak about keeping things clean but pulling off my registers throughout the house and cleaning them is not on the top of my cleaning list! LOL! Before putting the tape on the outside of my register, I cleaned the register vent first. I then dried the vent and applied rubbing alcohol to a cotton ball and wiped down the area I was going to apply the sticky side of the Velcro too. This worked like a charm! That Velcro is going nowhere and is fully secured!

Not enough Velcro? By taking the time to clean the vent, I used very little Velcro. I cut off about a 1/4 inch for each corner of my vents! So 128 inches of Velcro can go a long way! When applying the filter to the Velcro, I pressed down firmly on one end to make sure the filter was going to stick to the Velcro and then I was able to pull on the filter to make the filter taunt over the register.

Does it still keep dust and dander down in the house in using half the thickness of the filter? YES!! IT'S AMAZING!!! Each and every morning I would wake up to my glass top stove covered in dust! Not anymore!! Yes, there were little specs of dust on top of my stove, but nothing like it used to be! Also, there is plenty of air flow moving through the filter, so I don't have to worry about my system working hard.

It took a little bit of time and effort to cut appropriate size strips with rounded edges as the instructions suggest, and then to install. Product does make me more confident in the shower stall which had an extremely slick bottom, and all strips have adhered well. (Thanks to someone else who posted a picture of their approach to a pattern which I copied). I went with the 2-in wide version and would suggest that width for shower applications.

I'm generally satisfied with the purchase although a bad, persistent chemical smell endures. I'd read about shower mats having bad toxic smells and was hoping this product would allow me to avoid that issue, but I still notice the unpleasant aroma 3 weeks after installing. I even tried leaving baking soda on the strips overnight without much improvement. The smell is not as strong as the first week, but it's still there... if you are sensitive to smells be aware that this product does emanate some chemical odor. However, considering that a mat will get grime, gunk, and hair stuck underneath in the suction cups thus requiring cleaning every so often, these by contrast are maintenance-free once installed. Nothing sticks to the surface of the strips in my experience.

If you have a tight air handling system in your application, the filter will work just fine without noticeable obstruction of air flow. But in an old and large whole house hot air heating system there may be leaks in the ducts, then a small backpressure, generated by the filter on one of the air outlets, will divert some hot air into those leaks and into other rooms in the house. Such is my case. With just one air outlet filtered, the reduction of air flow from it is noticeable. With all air outlets filtered, much less so, the blower is forcing the air more evenly. Don't know how leaky the ducts inside the walls are, but in my case it is an acceptable trade off for cleaner air.

The problem is that the suction cup (original) was attached by a screw that went Through (if you can believe it) the center of the suction cup.  Recipe for failure.  Air leaks past the screw, carrying dust, and eventually it won't stick.I was looking for something that would fit OVER a screwhead, leaving the cup side intact.  Well.  These don't.That said, these are actually great cups.  I used a couple with a hook and they held for... well, they're still holding, supporting some stuff for a couple of weeks now with no sign of leaking air (clean the window really good before applying).So.  If you're going to use a hook over the knob on the cup, you're gonna love these things.  I really recommend them for that.  If you've got a moose that's trying to tell you how hot/cold it is.... not so much.

I had one of those plastic footstools and it broke within a year. This is very stable and even has a secure grip to make sure it doesn't move (came with additional rubber). It has three steps so all heights and I can safely reach the top of my cabinets.

I installed these about a week ago and so far so good! They are not rough on your feet. Easy to cut through with scissors. (The instructions say to round the corners.)  Hair and other debris have not gotten stuck on them. There is no recommended wait time after installing. (I saw similar products sometimes said to wait 12 hours after applying to make sure they stick.) I will try to report back in a few months, but when installing, I got the distinct impression the tape really wanted to stick and stick well.*update*  This has lined my bathtub for about 7 months now. It's as perfect as the day it was installed. That is with two adults taking  showers (one in the evening, one in the morning) so it gets wet at least twice a day. I will also give it major credit because Draino has made contact with the pieces closest to the drain twice, and still, it's as good as the day I put it in! It also survived 3 rounds of spray used to clean the walls of the shower. No yellowing. No signs of mold. I'm so happy I sprung for this version of no-slip tape over the cheaper versions.  Totally worth it.

The tile floor in our shower felt slippery underfoot, so I put down 3M slip-resistant tape.  They got the texturejust right.  It's just rough enough to make the floor feel safe when wet, but not too rough to be comfortableon bare feet.  I made sure the tiles were clean, then wiped with acetone on a paper towel.  After I put the tapedown, I used a rubber roller to make sure it was completely stuck.  Each floor tile has its own piece of 3M tape,and I rounded the corners of each piece of tape. Clean it with a cleanser.  Dry it well.  Wipe it again with alcohol, and you're ready to go.  Plan your tread pattern, cut the lengths, round the corners, and stick it down.  The product smells like a new vinyl shower curtain for a while, but that fades over time.  The 2" wide tread seems about right, and the length was more than enough for good coverage.The last treads I had lasted 5 years, and I'll be very happy if these last that long too. At first we thought it was too dense for air vent covers but gave them a try, through trial and error we now rate this a 5 star product with a HUGE exception; the supplied velcro is worthless.

To counter that problem we used GREATMAG 60 Name Badge Magnets, Magnetic Name Badge Holders, Magnetic Name Tags with 3 Magnets, super strong magnets, small measurements that hold the filter material very taunt to the vent cover (we use 8 per vent, three top & bottom then one on each side), works like a charm and makes removing/replacing a breeze. To match decor we merely spray painted them white and they are hardly noticeable.
We do not cover every vent, just the ones closet to us in bedrooms, living room etc... where we spend most of our time, we noticed if all vents were covered the central heating/cooling was taking too long to do its thing. The material does remove a lot of unwanted particles and is fairly dense, just use common sense.
Our heating/cooling guy said not covering all vents was a good idea and to NOT cover air intake vents, he recommended we let the main ac/heater filter handle that job.
Huge improvement in air quality, amazing what debris comes out of ducts and vents the filter material catches.
We plan on buying more to have on hand if that says anything.
If theres any small negative there is not a lot of material for $14 but comparing that price to 3M filtrete makes it a decent price/deal.

I genuinely hate it when home interior doors are cut too short. Especially when paired with hardwood floors. Even a minor gap under a door allows sound to bounce around - not to mention light, wind, dust, and bugs. Sound is one of my biggest problems - because I genuinely believe that when you shut a door, you don't want to be able to hear what is on the other side. Years ago I started to experiment with using "door feet" mainly meant for outside-facing doors inside. These tended to require removing a door first, or more complex construction. They usually added a strip of metal and rubber to the bottom of a door, effectively creating a flexible seal.

This product is like a more basic version of a door foot/cap, but it works by sticking a silicone strip to one side of the door. You might call it a door skirt or similar. The silicone is thick and spreads out into three strips closer to where it is designed to brush against the floor. Even though visually the design seemed perfect to me, I was highly skeptical of how well this product would actually stick and remain stuck to a door. The company even includes metal pin tacks which can be used to make the door skirt more permanently affixed - but with damage to your door.

I've thus far installed about seven of these products both in this brown color and in white. To my surprise, the adhesive has remained intact. This is despite the fact that I used them on doors which move over carpeting. That means the carpet pulls on the silicone strip as it moves in both directions - creating more pull on the glue. I'm guessing I will have to replace the each few years - which seems like a small price to pay given how inexpensive they are, as well as easy they are to install.

Installation requires a knife because you'll need to first place the fill strip along the door, and then cut it to size. This isn't hard, but requires steady hands a bit of patience to get right. Adhesive products such as this also require that you physically press the glued-on item to the based for a number of seconds to ensure a decent still. With that said, I can't see a skilled person taking more than 5-10 minutes to install one of these.

While it isn't always possible to cover each and every little gap under a door, this product will probably seal up at least 98% of any gaps between a door and a floor that you are interesting in closing. I've even used one of these strips to close some small gaps that ants were using to enter my home under a door that opens to a patio. If your goal is to easily and effectively shut out sound and the elements under most home doors, this product seems to work pretty well, and blends in nicely enough so it isn't much of an eyesore. Not hard to recommend this.

My old tub had a lot of pits and scratches and rust spots from years of scrubbing and age. Unfortunately, this made every type of suction-cup tub mat slide around and wrinkle up. After doing a lot of research, I found this product and ordered it. It works great. For installation, I also recommend a wallpaper seam roller of some sort and a small razor blade or box cutter. (Pictured below with the plain wooden handle is the "Warner 222 Plastic Flat Seam Roller with Double Bracket, 1-Inch Wide" for about $13 and the one with the red and black handle is the "MARSHALLTOWN The Premier Line E54D 2-Inch Flat Commercial Grade Solid Rubber Seam Roller with DuraSoft Handle" for about $21. Both of these and many others are available on Amazon as well.)

For my pattern, I cut the entire roll into 18" strips. Then I cut three of the 18" strips in half. This made seven 18" strips and six 9" strips. After scouring the tub with Comet and drying it really well with a fan, I began. First, I wiped the tub with rubbing alcohol and let it dry again. Second, I cut the strips and rounded the ends. Third, I laid all of the pieces down with the backing still on until I found a pattern I liked. (see finished photo for pattern I chose). Fourth, peeling the backing off of each piece, I carefully stuck each down. Fifth, I went on an epic three-hour journey to Home Depot and Menard's in search of something that would roll the strips down. (frustrating!) Anyway, I found what I needed and finished rolling them down, starting from the center and working my way to the edges. (This is where the razor blade came in. Sometimes bubbles formed and I carefully slit them and rolled them flat) Voila! I'm done and the strips work great. My tub is much safer now.

Please note:These are clear, so the scratches and small rust spots can be seen through the strips. (again, see photo) I'm okay with that, though, and am glad to just be able to shower safely.

I found the tape to not be very strong to the output of my air vent, and would often blow the tape off. I even cleaned the area with alcohol prior to installing but I think the air pressure is stronger that what the tape can handle.

As far as the filter, I left it up for a month and didn't see it really catch anything or discolor while being in front of the air vent like I thought I would. One thing I did notice, is it really limited the amount of air leaving the vent, which is to be expected but it made my AC stay on longer to achieve the desired room temperature (Studio Apartment)

Overall, I'm sure there are some use cases where this would help but didn't really do much for me.

In the process of moving recently, I often found myself needing to lift heavy appliances and furniture with very low clearance  (like a giant armoire, washing machine, commercial fridge, buffet, etc.) in order to get tri-wheel dollies positioned underneath for maneuvering in situations way too tight for an appliance dolly. I bought a pair of knock-offs to start with, but the lifting capacity wasnt enough, they got bent easily, and just failed to lift with loads heavier than ~70 lbs. As I result I did some damage to our wood floors trying to use an appliance dolly and the built-in fridge wheels while trying to get our oversized commercial fridge into place. Once I got fed up and bought a Viking Arm, getting some tri-wheel dollies under the fridge (already in a really tight space at that point) was simple this thing really can lift 350 lbs pretty easily! Subsequently I seem to find a use for this thing on a regular basis.

I have a table where the little suction cups between the metal frame and the glass table top had completely disintegrated into sticky gooey plastic blobs. No doubt the result of exposure to sun light which can be harsh on some materials.

I was afraid it would be difficult to find a matching replacement but was very happy to find the ANCIRS product page which had suction cups in various sizes and with different attachment options.

Since the original suction cups where stuck into holes within the metal table legs, some of the offered suction cups could be disregarded immediately. Since the original suction cups where all too far gone to get any meaningful measurements from them, I measured the hole size within the table legs which turned out to be 7.6mm or 0.3". This left me with either the 20mm or 30mm size suction cups (the size on the ANCIRS product page is the outer diameter of the suction cup and unrelated to the snap-in on the rear). From the product description I gathered that the 20mm size would work, but might be a loose fit while the 30mm size might be a struggle to insert but provide a more rigid fit.
I decided to buy the 30mm size and while it was indeed a bit of a struggle to get them into the holes, they are a perfect fit once they are properly in place.
I'm very happy with the purchase and hope these will last a good while. Even if they don't, the generous amount (30 of them in one bag) means that I can replace them multiple times before I have to buy them again (I'll be sure to keep the spares out of the sunlight).

I am very impressed with the Bosch version of the Black and Decker Workmate (which I used to own and this replaces for me) as it really is a well engineered and properly product designed item. The folding action is very easy and results in a sturdy platform for working on; which is the main requirement after all! In terms of materials the use of Aluminium rather than sheet steel for the frame means that there is no paint finish to chip and go rusty (if kept outside in a shed), no sharp edges and also results in a lighter item to carry around. I think the folded depth is a bit less that the Workmate too. I was intrigued by the use of Bamboo for the worktop pieces and they do seem to be very dense and harder that the usual plywood used for these surfaces so should be very durable in use. The finish on the Bamboo surfaces is quite shiny so I do find that work-pieces have a tendency to slip about so it would have been better to have a more matted finish but this will probably improve with use and wear (or you could run a bit of abrasive paper over it). I don't know if the tool tray is so useful but is handy for pencils and small tools - you can't keep things in it when the bench is folded though. One thing I did find with the tool tray is that it obstructs the front underside edge of the worktop so it is not possible to hook a clamp under the front edge which is slightly limiting in where you can position things. The only other item which might have been better is the cross bar at the front base of the frame, on the Workmate there is a full width step which you can rest a foot on to steady the bench, the Bosch one is quite flimsy so I would have liked this to be a bit sturdier so that it could perform a similar function. It's a shame that a great British invention was not further developed along these lines but that seems to be a familiar story! Really recommended if your Workmate is clapped out or you are considering a first time buy of a folding workbench.

I have installed it on my air vents for the past 2 months and it is effective in stopping dust from entering my room from the AC vents but at the cost of a roughly 50% reduction in the airflow. How did I conclude this? because it got a lot hotter when it was attached. And just today I removed the 2 month old filter and was going to attach a clean one. Whilst installing the clean one; I used my palm to check how much air flow was passing through with and without the filter. I was shocked that about 50% of the air was also being blocked. So I would accept some dust to enter as long as I can get 100% of the cold air from the AC vents. btw, I also ready have the fan speed turned to the maximum.

Overall you can use it if you have intense dust coming our of the vents; but if this was the case I'd look for a AC duct cleaning service instead.

I will not be using this filter anymore and I will repurpose this filter for maybe something else.

Original review below the horizontal line.

The useless tool / screw holder thing should be removed immediately upon opening. It's covered by the table half the time, blocks clamping on a large potion of a useful part of the bench, and even when reachable is shallow and awkward. The aluminium rivets can be easily drilled out.

The 20mm holes were initially something I was excited about, however there is little rhyme or reason to the hole pattern. Without really looking I presumed it would be a simple useful grid pattern. It is not at all. If the holes were actually in a grid the usefulness of the table would be increased dramatically.

As time goes on, my annoyance at the disparity in heights between the two surfaces grows.

The table could really do with another 2.5cm of travel to accommodate 10cm (making 2x4 wood - a very common size) more workable.

The positioning of the hardware near what holes are usable around the edges, as well as the positioning just generally being close to the edges, makes some clamping very awkward.

It's quite top heavy. Even light planing will have it trying to tip over, due to the light aluminium legs. Lots of vibration when sawing too.

Dropping score to 3 stars. It's... fine.

____________________________________________________

Four stars rather than 5 because there is a slight height difference between the two halves of the top. It might not matter to most people, but it impacts the work I do. In the order of 1-3 mm deviation across the faces.

Additional points lost for lack of 360 degree clearance around the table edges for clamping. The side with the handles is quite awkward. The little tray is also useless. I'm going to just cut it out of mine to free up clamping real estate.

It is however, sturdy, easy to fold away and deploy, good materials, and the holes included are great for making jigs (espeically if you have a 3d printer).

I'd buy it again, even with my issues with it.

No doubt as everyone else does I read all the reviews on different work benches.I was prepared to pay a premium to get a really good bench,as with most things in the long run it is actually more economical to buy the best you can in the beginning.I nearly didn't buy this bench due to the negatives i read on stability issues,however regardless of this i continued with my purchase on the grounds of my excellent history with Bosch products.The Bench is indeed incredibly easy to erect,and has a very low profile to stow away.The first thing that REALLY impressed me was the Bamboo worktops,AND the large worktop area,the Bamboo will be weather proof,and very durable well done Bosch!The clamping dogs stow on the plastic cross brace,again great idea!There is a storage tray for a tape + pencils etc-It is covered when the bench is open,however this is not a fault just a design constraint.The bench is very simple to uproot and move around with great locking mechanisms,its light and very easy to manoeuvre in and out of a vehicle/van,the clamping mechanism & handles seem well constructed,i haven't forced them but i take it from the fact the handle gets tight that the clamping must be done parallel,again i appreciate that mechanically the mechanism would be a lot weaker to allow this articulation of the top.Finally Stability/Build Like I said this Bench has many great qualities over others,the actual worktop being the very best I've seen by far.However after three months of use i can confirm this bench does have stability issues,even on level ground with all legs firmly seated there is flex in the legs,which causes a twisting in the framework with vigorous sawing etc.This somewhat shocked me in the early stages of ownership,to the point of nearly returning it.Why didn't I? Well like i said this bench does have lots going for it,so much so that i have kept it.Bosch should have made the aluminium legs of a thicker wall material and i think this would have resolved the issue,its aluminium so wouldn't have added much weight.The stability doesn't cause me any issues with smaller tasks,& general woodwork,Im a contractor so this will get used quite hard from time to time-so far so good.
REVIEW UPDATE!!!
Sadly as thought after time 6 Months this bench has started to fall apart,I'm constantly retightening screws & tweaking things,NO WAY could you ever carry out heavy sawing on this,it would definitely buckle and fall apart.Ive purely given this three stars,because some of this bench is excellent! IE the bamboo work tops,the way it quickly folds up into a very small space,the work top area is large.Treat this bench with kid gloves,as its fragile-Bosch is falling apart at the seams to be producing stuff like this! Bosch at one time always meant quality!
PLEASE READ!!! 1Yr Update!
Ok My review stands as before,However I can confirm after a year of use,NOTHING has actually broken or fallen apart,although I do CONSTANTLY have to tighten things up,screws come loose all the time.Ive upgraded my rating from 3 - 4 stars because of this.This bench has many,many good qualities.Ive left this out in the rain for a week! with NO adverse effects or issues with the bench.I really really hope BOSCH bring out an improved bench,I will be first in the que!! Its very easy to collapse & fold,& takes up hardly any room.Please Please BOSCH make the legs a little tighter & from thicker material & use different fasteners.

Overall this is a really badly implemented piece of equipment.
With this particular example I noticed the following problems and the nature of the faults would indicate that there is a generic problem with the design and production.

1. The overall bench is flimsy and disconcerting when try to saw or plane items held in the bench.
I measured 10mm of play in both axis when planing and sawing. This was with a restraining foot on the foot bar.
2. The two clamp handles were really stiff to turn. This is a problem with any sort of vice as the handles need to be spun to quickly move the jaws from one position to another. The reason is probably that the two threaded bars are passing through a badly made nylon threaded component that attaches to the moving top.
3. There is a 1mm step between the three surface parts making up the bench top. This stops any item sliding smoothly over the work surface or precision clamping.
4. All four 'blade-clamps' are incredibly tight in the worktop holes necessitating hammering in and removal with pliers.
5. Due to a design fault two of the holes are unusable as they are obstructed by part of the under-frame.
6. The two release buttons on the front legs are very stiff and when they release the scrape the skin of your thumb on the sharp cut-out they fit in.
7. An awful lot of the stress bearing components are made from plastic which could explain some of the flimsiness.

Postscript:
The bench is also 6cm taller than all of my other three work surfaces; Original Black & Decker, DIY Store Special and a set of 4 Saw-horses. This makes it difficutl to use with other benches.
I quick-clamped a piece of 25mm x 2mm steel diagonaly across the back frame of the bench and the side-ways stability was drastically improved.

I had almost given up on finding a proper folding workbench. Like many I have given-up on the original Black & Decker range since whey introduced the cheap plastic caps that the threads screw into, as these break all too often. Indeed the B&D range is so cheaply made that they provide no meaningful service life. The Draper, Clarke and Sealey versions are no better, although the Woolcraft range has some redeeming features but lacks outright strength.

But the new Bosch PWB 600 is in a different league to them all.

The machining, fit and finish of the load-bearing parts is incredible. The folding action is super smooth, easy to accomplish and produces either a stable platform or an ultra thin square shape for easy storage. The extra large top deck is welcome, as is the use of bamboo and you can even snug-up a stool or similar as the overhang at the rear can cater for your knees. The dogs are well made, do the business and stow away at the rear of the lower green bar with the Bosch logo. Of equal quality is the tool tray, which is a well finished metal tray that should cope with robust use and it does not get in the way. The black bar near floor level means you can slip a foot or toe on it to provide extra stability when wrestling with more challenging project.

Hard to find many negatives, but being picky I would have liked the imbedded metal ruler to fit flush with the surface and have inches as well as metric. A slightly larger span to clamp larger parts, without resorting to the dogs, would have been nice too.

Clearly designed with the professional in mind, the price (given the quality) will attract the premium end of the DIY market. For the DIYers that have suffered a failure of the other types of workbench should look at this too, whatever their budget.

A must have item for the mobile professional or the DIYer who is looking for a product built to last - fantastic!

Delivered quickly by Yodel to North Essex (Saffron Walden). Arrived in Bosch box in good condition.  Simply unpacked it, had a quick glimpse at the instruction book just to be sure and opened bench out ready for work in seconds, it was as easy as that. Nothing to put together, no additional tools, easy to operate and light to carry yet feels strong. Ingenious design by Bosch. Simple to collapse and fold away, no getting fingers caught or struggling, it's a very easy bench to operate and finished to a high standard. Made in India written on box but don't let that put you off buying one of these, this is typical German quality. Very slim when stowed. My wife will be able to operate this with ease it's so simple to set up and take down. Has a very large bench top when open, giving a nice big flat work surface. The red plastic clamps which fit into the ready made holes of the work top can be stored underneath on the framework in purpose made holes, a feature I like because you know where they are and are easy to retrieve when you want to use them. Has a useful indent/tray area at the front for leaving a pencil or some screws while you are working. Handles work well and I noticed that the threaded bar connected to them and the vice/worktop even has a dab of grease on to keep it running smoothly. Being a keen DIY 56 year old with a lot of projects on the go including constructing a decking verandah outside our new conservatory, I think this will prove to be a good purchase and because of the build quality it will probably see me out!  I recommend this product. UPDATE.3/6/13.  Had this for a week now and have used it mostly for sawing 4 x 2 timber.  I have to agree with a previous reviewer who said that it wobbled about when he was sawing wood.  This is because of the excellent height of the bench and the fact that it has many joints in the fold out/in legs. I'm still glad I bought it. It's quality. I have since also purchased a B&D 301 from Amazon at a very good price. This is slightly more stable than this Bosch 600 when sawing wood, but the height is too low for me. I was put off buying the B&D 536 or 825 by all the negative views, but now I'm wondering??

I'm sure that this filter will work but it's not set up to where it can be easily or evenly cut.  The tape gives up a few days after application, but the filter material seems like it would do the job in keeping irritants that blow from the air ducts out of the air.  It's very important to include a lot of tape as some vents aren't flat and need a lot more work to cover.  Not only that, but the force of the air can easily remove tape that doesn't have a strong grip on it.  The velcro side would work fine.  But the sticky tape side of it doesn't hold it in place.  So that was a real problem for me.  Every fall through spring when my furnace runs, so do my allergies to the extreme.  I can't afford air duct cleaning and bleaching and my landlord won't.  So I definitely need something that's gonna keep out the dust and allergy air allergens from my home.  This will if a lot stronger holding tape was included and a lot more of it.  It wouldn't be a problem taping some of the filter together either if pieces were pre cut.  But that's not too bad as long as there's enough tape so it can all be installed on the vents.
